<HEAD>With PM-Trinidad Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Has No Plans to Send Forces to Trinidad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New material, editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> has no plans to send
military forces to <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, where Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur Robinson</PERSON>
and more than 30 others are being held hostage by Moslem rebels,
the <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   At the same time, deputy spokesman <PERSON>Richard Boucher</PERSON> criticized
<LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION>'s involvement with the rebels, saying it has provided some
training for the insurgents. But he said there was no apparent
direct link between <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and the hostage-taking, which occurred
last <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Boucher refused comment on reports that <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military assets
were being deployed in the vicinity of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> but said ``there
are no plans for <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military intervention.''
   The USS Roosevelt paid a scheduled visit to <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION> <DATE>July
20-23</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> said. The carrier is now in port in <LOCATION>Norfolk</LOCATION>. The
<ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> has 10 ships in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> on what the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> calls ``routine
exercises.''
   <PERSON>Boucher</PERSON> said there have been no reports of injury to the
estimated 6,000 Americans living in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>.
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> was keeping up to date on developments after
returning to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> late <DATE>Sunday</DATE> after a weekend at his vacation
home in <LOCATION>Kennebunkport</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION>.
   ``We fully support the government of Prime Minister (<PERSON>Arthur</PERSON>)
<PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> and hope for a peaceful solution to the situation there,''
said <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Alixe Glen</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials said any direct <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> role had been all but ruled
out. Even sending <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> experts on hostage negotiations _ discussed
informally on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> between the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and
representatives of the <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> government _ had been ruled out,
sources said.
   ``The Trinidadians would like to find a solution on their own
without any outside assistance. They'd just rather settle it
themselves,'' the official said.
   The administration has hailed <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s government as a model
of democracy, and the attempted coup was viewed with distress in
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>, the leader of a Moslem sect, launched the coup attempt
late <DATE>Friday</DATE> by seizing the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION> and
capturing <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> and about 40 other hostages.
   <PERSON>Angus Khan</PERSON>, the ambassador from <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> to the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, said the negotiations between his government and the
``terrorists over the release of the hostages are very delicate.''
He refused to say more.
</TEXT>
