<HEAD>Moslem Leader Has Fought With Government for Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf, `Most East...' with 1 graf to CORRECT
description of island's population. No pickup. Abu Bakr is
pronounced AH-boo BAH-kuhr.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Trinidad-Uprising, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>, the Moslem leader whose
rebels captured the prime minister and his Cabinet in a coup
attempt, has been fighting with the government for years.
   Most recently, <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> has been involved in a dispute over medical
supplies and pharmaceuticals reportedly donated by <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and
prohibited by customs agents from entering the country.
   One of the first things <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> did after taking the leaders
captive was accuse the government of refusing to let him distribute
free medicine to the poor people of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>.
   Members of his sect, <ORGANIZATION>Jamaat al-Muslimeen</ORGANIZATION>, have long been
perceived by many Trinidadians as violent outlaws, although they
proclaim moralistic motives for their actions.
   Bakr, in his mid-40s, founded <ORGANIZATION>Jamaat al-Muslimeen</ORGANIZATION>, Arabic for
``Group of Moslems,'' six years ago.
   He has said he does not recognize ``man's laws,'' but only ``the
law of almighty Allah.''
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, he said he understood ``the present suffering of the
people'' and that Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur Robinson</PERSON> had been
overthrown by God.
   ``God has removed him,'' <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> said on government television.
``No man, including me, has power. ... He gave us victory over the
prime minister.''
   Bakr, his 200 to 250 followers and their wives and children live
on a commune in western <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>.
   In <DATE>1988</DATE>, police raided the commune, seizing weapons and
ammunition and arresting 34 members of the sect on charges of
larceny, robbery, illegal possession of weapons, rape and murder.
   Bakr, a former policeman, said then his vigilantes were waging a
war against ``the menace of cocaine.''
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, he said, ``We will stop the incest, robbery, and
drugs which there was no hope for the present regime to stop.''
   Moslems make up <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT> of the population of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, a former British colony just off the northeast coast of
<LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>. Of the nation's 1.3 million people, about <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> are
of African descent and the same proportion is of East Indian
descent.
   Most of the <LOCATION>East Indians</LOCATION> are Hindu. Most of the <LOCATION>Africans</LOCATION> are
Roman Catholic or Protestant. The nation's small Moslem population
is mostly East Indians with some <LOCATION>Africans</LOCATION>. But the black Moslem
population has grown since the black power movement began 20 years
ago, and <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>'s sect is the largest among them.
</TEXT>
