<HEAD>About 400,000 Moslems Scattered Across Caribbean</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trinidad, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERNAN TURNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 400,000 Moslems make the
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> their home, but most are East Indians who disdain the
radical politics of black Moslems like those who are holding
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s government hostage.
   <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, black <PERSON>Moslem Abu Bakr</PERSON> took over <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> and
threatened to kill the prime minister and much of his Cabinet.
   Bakr is a fundamentalist who has developed strong support from
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s poor black community. His <ORGANIZATION>Jamaat al-Muslimeen</ORGANIZATION> sect has
an eight-acre commune in western <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>, where more than 250
men, women and children live. There is a large mosque, day care
center, school and kitchens for the homeless.
   Bakr has close ties with <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and has often stated that Islamic
principles must dominate society.
   But few East Indian Moslems support views like <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>'s and
tensions between Moslems of East Indian and African descent _ two
groups that rarely mix _ have been high.
   Many East Indians consider the black Moslems political
opportunists inspired more by the black power movement than by
traditional Islam. <PERSON>Stokely Carmichael</PERSON>, the black power advocate of
the <DATE>1960s</DATE> in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, was born in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>.
   Among the region's political leaders, prominent Moslems include
East Indian President <PERSON>Noor Hassanali</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and Prime Minister
<PERSON>Hamilton Green</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION>, a black who converted to Islam in the
<DATE>1960s</DATE>.
   The first Moslems came to the region to work in the sugar cane
fields, either as black slaves in the <DATE>1700s</DATE> or as indentured
servants from <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> 100 years later.
   Now domed mosques can be found on a dozen <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> islands, but
the heaviest concentrations of Moslems are on the islands of
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> and in <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Suriname</LOCATION> on the South
American mainland.
   ``One of the region's strongest religious trends today is the
movement toward Islam among blacks,'' says freelance writer <PERSON>Larry
Luxner</PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION>San Juan</LOCATION>. In the <DATE>last 20 years</DATE>, many blacks
have converted to Islam.
   Luxner, who has written extensively on Moslems in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>,
estimates that Trinidad-Tobago and <LOCATION>Suriname</LOCATION> each have 100,000
Moslems and <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> 120,000.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> is mostly a Hindu and Christian nation of
1.3 million people. About <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT> of the population is Moslem,
with those of East Indian and African descent each make up <PERCENT>40
percent</PERCENT> of the Moslem population.
   Writing in the Arabic magazine <LOCATION>Aramco World</LOCATION> in <DATE>1987</DATE>, <PERSON>Luxner</PERSON> said
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> had 85 mosques, <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> 133 and <LOCATION>Suriname</LOCATION>, formerly Dutch
<LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION>, 150. He said <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>Suriname</LOCATION>'s 400,000 people were
Moslem, the highest percentage in any country in the <LOCATION>Western
Hemisphere</LOCATION>.
   There are also 2,500 Moslems in <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>, most of them
Palestinians who arrived between <DATE>1958</DATE> and <DATE>1962</DATE>, <PERSON>Luxner</PERSON> said.

</TEXT>
