<HEAD>US Rules Out Military Intervention in Trinidad</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 6: ``Aronson, who,'' to identify second minister;
SUBS 9th graf: ``As in,'' to delete reference to rebel curfew.
Trinidad curfew is a government measure</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trinidad Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Monday</DATE> there are no
plans for <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military intervention to bring an end to the
Moslem-led insurrection against the elected government in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>.
   While refusing comment on reports of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military maneuvers in
the area, deputy spokesman <PERSON>Richard Boucher</PERSON> suggested that a
military solution had been ruled out.
   At the same time, <PERSON>Boucher</PERSON> criticized <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION>'s involvement with
the rebels, saying it has provided some training for the
insurgents. But he said there was no apparent direct link between
<LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and hostage-taking which occurred last <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>, the leader of a Moslem sect, launched the coup attempt
by seizing the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> building in <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION> and capturing
Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur N.R. Robinson</PERSON> and about 40 other hostages.
   <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> and one other goverment minister were believed to have
been shot in the leg early in the coup attempt, and both have been
getting medical attention, said <PERSON>Bernard W. Aronson</PERSON>, assistant
secretary of state for inter-American affairs.
   Trinidad government spokesman <PERSON>Gregory Shaw</PERSON> identified the second
victim as Justice Minister <PERSON>Selwyn Richardson</PERSON>, and said both men
were in stable condition. <ORGANIZATION>Shaw</ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> had been shot in both
feet, not the legs
   <PERSON>Aronson</PERSON>, who spoke in an interview on the ``MacNeil-Lehrer
NewsHour'' on the <ORGANIZATION>Public Broadcasting System</ORGANIZATION>, also said people were
killed in the coup attempt but said the department did not have a
figure on the casualties. He said none of them was a high-ranking
government official, but he declined to identify the victims
further.
   The <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> crisis has some of the earmarks of the situation in
<LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION> <DATE>seven years ago</DATE> when a radical leftist movement took power.
In that case, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and several other <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>
countries decided to oust the radicals.
   As in <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION>, the insurgents have shown a willingness to use
extremist methods to advance their cause.
   In both <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, there were signs of involvement by
anti-American elements from abroad. In <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION>, the leadership
there had close links to <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION> while in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> has been
allied with the rebels. Also, in both cases, a major concern of
<LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> has been the well being of thousands of Americans
residing in the two countries.
   But a major difference between the two situations is that
whereas virtually all of the Americans in <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION> were students at
a medical school, the 6,000 Americans in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> are dispersed
around the island and are less vulnerable to a mass hostage-taking.
   The international political climate also has undergone a
dramatic transformation since <DATE>1983</DATE>, a period when Cold War tensions
were at a peak.
   There is little indication that the events in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> will have
an impact beyond that country's borders. This was not the case in
<DATE>1983</DATE>, when members of the <ORGANIZATION>Organization of Eastern Caribbean States</ORGANIZATION>
asked for the dispatch of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> troops.
   Beyond that, American officials said government officials in
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> have indicated a desire to resolve the crisis without
outside help.
</TEXT>
