<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Freed, Others Remain Captives in Trinidad Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to CORRECT prime minister's initials,
ADDS that no details of release immediately available, background.
Picks up 11th pvs, `Bakr said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur N.R.
Robinson</PERSON> was freed by his Moslem captors <DATE>today</DATE> but other officials
held hostage were not released, the government announced.
   Attorney General <PERSON>Anthony Smart</PERSON> gave no details of how and under
what conditions the prime minister, who had been shot in both feet
during the uprising, was freed. But the release of <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> alone
indicated the 5-day-old standoff between the government and Moslem
extremists was not over.
   ``We continue to pray for the safe return of the rest of the
hostages,'' Smart told state radio.
   He said <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> was the only one of the 41 hostages released.
   Smart said <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON>, who was freed at <TIME>1:20 p.m. EDT</TIME>, ``is in
good spirits.''
   The siege began <DATE>Friday</DATE> when radical Moslems led by <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>
stormed <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and the government-run television station in
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s capital city. Bakr has accused the government of
mismanagement.
   The release came after a day of conflicting reports over the
progress of negotiations to end the hostage siege, which has
plunged this <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> nation of 1.3 million residents off
northeast <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> into chaos.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> had said by telephone that he had
accepted an agreement under which he would resign and <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> and his
men would be granted amnesty.
   But government officials said <DATE>today</DATE> that no such agreement
existed and that <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> had made the statement under duress.
   <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> said <DATE>earlier today</DATE> that the rebels agreed that <PERSON>Winston
Dookeran</PERSON>, the deputy prime minister, would replace <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> when he
steps down. Dookeran was released from the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> building
<DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The interim government would be a coalition consisting of
representatives of all major political parties, along with <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>'s
<ORGANIZATION>Jamaat al-Muslimeen</ORGANIZATION> group.
   The group, which is believed to number 250 to 300, has blamed
<PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> for widespread poverty in this once-oil rich <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>
nation near <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>. It has little support among the populace.
   Bakr is a former policeman who converted to Islam in <DATE>1980</DATE> and
has long considered himself a champion of the downtrodden. He
founde <ORGANIZATION>Jamaat al-Muslimeen</ORGANIZATION>, which means the <ORGANIZATION>Moslem Group</ORGANIZATION> in Arabic,
in <DATE>1984</DATE>.
   Robinson easily won parliamentary elections in <DATE>1986</DATE>. Under the
constitution, the next elections don't have to be held until <DATE>1991</DATE>.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, security forces exchanged gunfire with the rebels at
<ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and at the government television station. Three
buildings in and around the TV complex were set ablaze but no
injuries were reported.
   At least nine people _ six rebels, two police officers and a
civilian _ have been killed since the siege began, and the
instability has spawned massive looting in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, a
two-island nation of 1.3 million people. State radio said some
looters were shot <DATE>Monday</DATE> but gave no details.
   Bakr has ties to <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and it is believed he has received
funding from that country. In a conversation with local radio
today, he said he had no regrets over what he had done.
   ``I hope we can settle it in love,'' he said.
   Asked if the siege could end in violence, he said, ``Everyone
will die at some time in their lives.''
</TEXT>
