<HEAD>U.S. Voices Support for Besieged Leader of Trinidad</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts grafs 9-10, ``Later, the State</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> expressed ``strong
support'' <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s prime minister, a captive of
black Moslem rebels who took over the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> island's parliament.
   President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> was spending the weekend relaxing at his
oceanfront <DATE>summer</DATE> home here, but he and national security adviser
<PERSON>Brent Scowcroft</PERSON> were kept abreast of the attempted coup, a
spokeswoman said.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>, who spent the morning on the tennis courts and boating,
attended the wedding of a second cousin in <TIME>late afternoon</TIME>.
   Deputy press secretary <PERSON>Alixe Glen</PERSON> said <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and Scowcroft were
``following the situation carefully'' in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, a
former British colony off the coast of <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> that gained
independence in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
   ``We maintain our strong support for the Democratic government
of Prime Minister (<PERSON>Arthur</PERSON>) <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON>,'' <PERSON>Ms. Glen</PERSON> said.
   ``It appears that no American citizens are in any danger. The
situation seems limited to one building,'' she said.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> have not yet asked for help, but the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> would consider the request if they do, she said.
   <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> and several members of his cabinet were being held
hostage in the parliament in <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION> by rebels led by former
policeman <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>, leader of a Moslem sect that said it recognizes
no government but ``the law of almighty Allah.''
   Later, the <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> issued this written statement:
   ``We condemn yesterday's attempt by a violent extremist group to
overthrow the democratic government of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>. We call
upon the parties in this attempted coup to release the hostages
under their control and to surrender to the legislative
constitutional authority of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>. This violent
attack on the government has no support from the people of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>
and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> who have enjoyed a long tradition of democratic
government. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> fully supports the elected government
and is consulting closely with it and other interested governments
in the region.''
   An administration official who accompanied <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> to <LOCATION>Maine</LOCATION> said
the army was still loyal to the prime minister and his
four-year-old government.
   On another international hotspot, <LOCATION>Liberia</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Ms. Glen</PERSON> said, ``The
situation has not changed. We're following it closely.''
   The beleaguered government of President <PERSON>Samuel Doe</PERSON> has been
under siege for weeks in that West African nation. Rebel leader
<PERSON>Charles Taylor</PERSON> claimed <DATE>Friday</DATE> to have established his own
government, even though street fighting continued.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>, getting a weekend respite from the drawn out negotiations
with Democrats over the budget deficit, brought his wife, <PERSON>Barbara</PERSON>,
daughter, <PERSON>Dorothy LeBlond</PERSON>, and several grandchildren with him
<DATE>Friday</DATE> on the flight from <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION>Pease Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Newington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.H.</LOCATION>
   He also gave his taciturn <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> nominee, <PERSON>David H.
Souter</PERSON>, a ride home to <LOCATION>New Hampshire</LOCATION>. Before heading off to visit
his mother at a <LOCATION>Concord</LOCATION> nursing home, <PERSON>Souter</PERSON> said it felt ``damn
good'' to be back in the <ORGANIZATION>Granite State</ORGANIZATION>.
   This was the Bushes' third visit to their vacation home since
Memorial Day.
   President and <PERSON>Mrs. Bush</PERSON> attended the wedding of a second cousin,
<PERSON>Ruben Andrus Holden</PERSON> V, 37, of <LOCATION>Marshfield</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, to <PERSON>Pamela Anne
Grindle</PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>, at <ORGANIZATION>St. Ann</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Episcopal Church</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Kennebunkport</LOCATION>.
   The stone church, which overlooks the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>, is where the
Bushes attend <DATE>Sunday</DATE> services. Guests were required to walk through
a portable metal detector.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Bush</PERSON> will stay behind when the president heads back to the
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>. The president will return here to
<PERSON>Walker</PERSON>'s Point on <DATE>Aug. 10</DATE> and stay until Labor Day.
</TEXT>
