<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Trinidad Siege to End</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur N.R.
Robinson</PERSON> and the chief negotiator for Moslem extremists said <DATE>Monday</DATE>
they have reached agreement to end a 4-day-old hostage siege.
   Robinson is one of 41 hostages reported held since <DATE>Friday</DATE> by
black Moslem extremists led by <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>.
   Justice and <ORGANIZATION>National Security</ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON>Selwyn Richardson</PERSON>,
speakig from inside <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> where the uprising began, said the
agreement called for <ORGANIZATION>Robinson</ORGANIZATION>'s immediate resignation with
elections to be held within 90 days.
   <PERSON>Richardson</PERSON> said the government had granted amnesty to the Moslem
radicals involved in the insurgency, which has left at least nine
people dead, according to officials.
   Speaking by telephone from inside <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> said the
agreement was reached after ``very difficult bargaining.''
   The prime minister said he instructed Col. <PERSON>Joe Theodore</PERSON>, head of
the <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Tobago Defense Force</ORGANIZATION>, to ``make necessary
arrangements for the evacuation (of hostages and rebels) as soon as
possible.''
   Chief rebel negotiator <PERSON>Bilal Abdullah</PERSON>, speaking next on the
telephone, said: ``I wish to totally corroborate what Prime
Minister <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> has just said.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION> spokesman Maj. <PERSON>Dave Williams</PERSON> reported earlier <DATE>Monday</DATE> that
the Moslems were armed with AK-47 assault rifles, pistols and
grenades.
   In the first official casualty count, <PERSON>Williams</PERSON> said at least
nine people had died in the fighting since <DATE>Friday</DATE>. He said Anglican
negotiator <PERSON>Knolly Clarke</PERSON> told him additional bodies were inside the
parliament building, but it was not known how many.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> is just off northeast <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>, and is a former
British colony that gained independence in <DATE>1962</DATE>. It has been
wracked in recent years by declining oil revenues and economic
doldrums, including high unemployment.
</TEXT>
