<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits Trinidad, No Damage Or Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to hyphenate Port-of-Spain, CORRECT its
population to 55,800. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `A security ...</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ A strong earthquake shook people
awake on the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> island of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> <DATE>early today</DATE> but police
said they had no reports of injuries or damage.
   The quake, the strongest in the area in 78 years, measured 6.9
on the Richter scale and struck at <TIME>2:17 a.m.</TIME> about 50 miles
southeast of the capital of <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Geological
Survey</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Earthquake Information Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Golden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colo</LOCATION>.
   ``No damage, no injuries. We just got a little shake and that's
all,'' said Lt. Velfukr Muhammed at police headquarters in the
capital of 55,800 people.
   ``I was in bed at the time and that woke me and everyone else in
the house,'' said <PERSON>Lionel Dixon</PERSON>, news editor of <ORGANIZATION>Radio Trinidad</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>.
   A security guard at the station, <LOCATION>San Keralli</LOCATION>, said the building
shook for about 40 seconds. <PERSON>Dixon</PERSON> said some people ran into the
street in the suburb where he lives.
   <PERSON>Frank Baldwin</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>USGS</ORGANIZATION> physical science technician in <LOCATION>Golden</LOCATION>,
said the epicenter appeared to have been in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> about 420
miles east of <LOCATION>Caracas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>, in a seismic area lying on the
boundary between the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and the South American crustal
plates of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   The quake was the area's largest since a magnitude 7.2 temblor
on <DATE>Jan. 23, 1910</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> is an island in the republic of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, a
member of the <ORGANIZATION>British Commonwealth</ORGANIZATION>. About 1.2 million people live
in the oil-producing republic, which covers an area about the size
of <LOCATION>Delaware</LOCATION> and is one of the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION>'s most prosperous countries.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage.
</TEXT>
