<HEAD>30 Died in Coup Attempt; Trinidad Will Prosecute Rebels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with government saying 30 people died during the
coup attempt, no deals struck with rebels will be honored. TRIMS.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ A failed coup attempt by Moslem
extremists and widespread looting that resulted left at least 30
people dead and 150 wounded in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, a government spokesman
said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   The authorities expect to find more bodies in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, where
the prime minister and other government ministers were held
hostage, and in a police station that was gutted by a car-bomb and
fire, spokesman <PERSON>Gregory Shaw</PERSON> said.
   Previous reports had said about 20 people died in the coup
attempt, which began <DATE>Friday</DATE> with a raid on <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and a
government TV station.
   <ORGANIZATION>Shaw</ORGANIZATION> also confirmed for the first time that Prime Minister <PERSON>N.R.
Robinson</PERSON>, after being shot in the leg, signed agreements to resign,
turn over power to a caretaker government and grant amnesty to the
rebels.
   ``All the agreements were signed under duress, all under
gunpoint, all of which are completely invalid,'' <PERSON>Shaw</PERSON> told
reporters at a news conference.
   <ORGANIZATION>Shaw</ORGANIZATION> said that the coup leader, <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON>, and his band of 111
militants had dropped their demands before surrendering on
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and releasing their remaining 46 hostages. A total of 55
hostages had been held.
   ``They caved in completely,'' he said. ``They surrendered
unconditionally.
   Officials have said they will press charges against <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> and
those who joined him in the coup attempt.
   <PERSON>Shaw</PERSON> said soldiers expect to go into <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> and the nearby
police station on <DATE>Friday</DATE> to search for bodies and unexploded bombs.
Soldiers standing outside the buildings said they were waiting one
day to go inside because of fears of time-delayed explosives.
   The security forces also evacuated 2,000 to 3,000 people from
the vicinity of the government television station, where 29
hostages were held after the building was seized last <DATE>Friday</DATE>. That
building also will be searched.
   <PERSON>Shaw</PERSON> said the dead included looters shot by the security forces,
but he gave no breakdown.
   The capital was quiet <TIME>this morning</TIME>. People remained indoors,
under a <TIME>6 p.m.</TIME> to noon curfew that remained in effect.
   State radio said <PERSON>Leo des Vignes</PERSON>, a junior government minister
taken hostage <DATE>Friday</DATE> and released a day later, died of a heart
attack <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in a hospital. He had been shot in the heel.
   Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON>Winston Dookeran</PERSON> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that
``appropriate charges'' would be brought against the militants.
   Asked whether the charges would include murder and treason,
<PERSON>Dookeran</PERSON> said it would be up to the judicial authorities to decide.
   Bakr, a former policeman who converted to Islam and considers
himself a champion of the downtrodden, was under heavy guard along
with the other 111 rebels at army headquarters in <LOCATION>Chaguerames</LOCATION> in
<LOCATION>northwest Trinidad</LOCATION>.
   The freed hostages spent the night at <LOCATION>Camp Ogden</LOCATION>, another army
base near the capital of <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>, for medical exams and
treatment.
   Bakr had demanded <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON>'s ouster, accusing him of corruption
and blaming him for widespread poverty in this once oil-rich
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> nation of 1.3 million people.
   The 63-year-old prime minister was freed <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> and
hospitalized for treatment of a leg wound suffered in the attack as
well as exhaustion and glaucoma.
   The defense chief, Col. <PERSON>Joe Theodore</PERSON>, said <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> had agreed to
surrender <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, four days after the siege began.
   ``I just think they were worn down,'' he said of the rebels.
``They just wanted out. They had come to the conclusion they had
failed.''
   The defense chief said the rebels had agreed to leave all their
explosives and ammunition on the speaker's table in the Parliament
building.
   Officials said the rebels had been armed with AK-47 assault
rifles, vintage World War II rifles, pump-action shotguns, pistols
and grenades.
   The coup attempt began <DATE>Friday</DATE> when armed rebels stormed the
state television station and the Parliament building, taking top
government officials and others captive. They also bombed and
burned down the police station.
   The attack set off a wave of looting.
   Hundreds of people took to the streets, ransacking stores and
warehouses and carrying away everything from food to television
sets. Damage was estimated at <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> and food and medicine
were beginning to run short. It was the country's worst violence
since a black power uprising in the early <DATE>1970s</DATE>.
   Dookeran said a state of emergency, including the islandwide
curfew, would remain in effect until the country gets back to
normal.
</TEXT>
