<HEAD>Envoy Says Food, Other Help Readied</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trinidad, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> is preparing
emergency assistance for this beleaguered <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> country, but
there are no plans to send military reinforcements, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
ambassador said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   ``We haven't been asked and we aren't considering any type of
military support,'' Ambassador <PERSON>Charles Gargano</PERSON> said at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S.
Embassy</ORGANIZATION>, a few blocks from the state <ORGANIZATION>Television House</ORGANIZATION> where a
radical Moslem group has held hostages since <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The group also seized the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament House</ORGANIZATION> and is holding
hostages there, including government officials. Prime Minister
<PERSON>Arthur N.R. Robinson</PERSON> was freed <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, five days after being
seized, the attorney general said.
   Because of widespread looting, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> could face food
shortages, and the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> is preparing emergency supplies,
<PERSON>Gargano</PERSON> said.
   He said a force of some 200 Caribbean soldiers were standing by
on <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION> to help if requested.
   The ambassador, who has been staying in the <ORGANIZATION>Embassy</ORGANIZATION> along with
12 other diplomatic personnel and six Marine guards, said he is in
regular contact with Trinidadian officials.
   He said there are no signs of splintering in the government or
security forces, and there is no popular support for the rebels.
   ``The government is in total control of the country,'' he said.
   <PERSON>Gargano</PERSON>, named in <DATE>1987</DATE>, said the crisis ``came out of the blue
for us. In fact, we were quite shocked. This country appeared to be
a model of democracy.''
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> stakes here are high, he said. He said there are 2,000
to 4,000 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> citizens in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, including many Trinidadians who
hold dual citizenship.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> is a major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade partner in the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> and has
been a pro-American democracy for its three decades of nationhood,
he said.
   ``Things have been moving apace in terms of democratization in
this hemisphere. We would like to see it continue as a strong
democracy,'' <PERSON>Gargano</PERSON> said.
   He said the Moslem group led by former <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> policeman <PERSON>Abu
Bakr</PERSON> has been controversial in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and has made anti-American
statements.
   ``Our impression is that it was a tiny fanatical sect,'' he
said, estimating <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>'s followers at 250 to 350 people.
   He said some members of the group have traveled to <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and
``there is some evidence of training given to some members.'' He
said they also have received funding from <LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION>. But <PERSON>Gargano</PERSON> added
there was no evidence of Libyan involvement in their move against
the government.
</TEXT>
