<TEXT>
Language: <FP=105> English </F>
Article Type:<ORGANIZATION>CSO</ORGANIZATION> 

<FP=106> [Article by <PERSON>Judy Diptee</PERSON>] </F>
  [Text] Foreign missions in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> have come 
together to assist the <ORGANIZATION>Government</ORGANIZATION> in tackling the illicit drug 
trade. 
  Officials at the <ORGANIZATION>French Embassy</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>UK High Commission</ORGANIZATION>, the 
<ORGANIZATION>US Embassy</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Canadian High Commission</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>last week</DATE> that 
they hold ad hoc, informal meetings to consider the requirements 
of the <ORGANIZATION>T&amp;T Government</ORGANIZATION> and how best they can each serve these 
needs. 
  The objective of these meetings, they say, is to exchange 
information so that projects are co-ordinated and to ensure that 
efforts are not duplicated. 
  The French have been identified as the experts on money 
laundering, the Canadians on training and equipment, the <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> on 
drug interdiction and the British on training. 
  <PERSON>Jacques Venne</PERSON>, delegate for the <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Caribbean Technical 
and International Police</ORGANIZATION> Co-operation (SCTIP) attached to the 
<ORGANIZATION>French Embassy</ORGANIZATION>, said that <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> was designated the 
regional centre of SCTIP operations on <DATE>September 27</DATE>. Director of 
SCTIP (International) Jean-Louise Ottavi visited for the opening 
on his way to <LOCATION>Aruba</LOCATION> to attend an <ORGANIZATION>Interpol Conference</ORGANIZATION>. 
  This country, he said, was chosen because of its 
geographical 
location and because of this <ORGANIZATION>Government</ORGANIZATION>'s interest in dealing 
with the illicit drug trade. The Jamaican office, he added, was 
closed in favour of reinforcing the newly-opened centre in 
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>. 
  The <ORGANIZATION>Paris Government</ORGANIZATION>, he said, has already released "a good 
budget" for training a special team of police officers in money 
laundering, starting from the end of <DATE>October</DATE>. The officers are 
expected to undergo an intensive training session in <LOCATION>Martinique</LOCATION>. 
  Emphasising that his <ORGANIZATION>Embassy</ORGANIZATION> offers assistance on the basis 
of discussions with this <ORGANIZATION>Government</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Venne</PERSON> said: "We are here as 
advisers, not to say what to do." 
  Head of the <ORGANIZATION>Office of Strategic Services</ORGANIZATION> (OSS) <PERSON>Lance Selman</PERSON> 
pointed out that the Customs and <ORGANIZATION>Excise Division</ORGANIZATION> as well as the 
banking sector needed to be educated about money laundering. 
"One can't talk of counter-narcotics and not money laundering. 
In the final analysis it is money that drives the trade," he 
commented. 
  His office, <PERSON>Selman</PERSON> said, has been mandated to develop the 
capabilities to deal with money laundering. 
  Stating that his country's contribution has been "very 
modest" to date, Canadian High Commissioner <PERSON>Jean Nadeau</PERSON> said on 
<DATE>Friday</DATE> that <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> has been offering participation in short-term 
observer/attendance programmes. These exercises, he explained, 
involved exposure to the <ORGANIZATION>Royal Canadian Mounted Police</ORGANIZATION> in their 
drug control operations. 
  Two T&amp;T officers will be attending such a session later 
this 
month. Besides training sessions, <PERSON>Nadeau</PERSON> said, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> has 
donated a small amount of communications equipment to the 
<ORGANIZATION>Ministry of National Security</ORGANIZATION> and has made a financial 
commitment to assist in the renovation of the <ORGANIZATION>Narcotics Unit</ORGANIZATION>. 
  Indirectly, the <ORGANIZATION>Canadian Government</ORGANIZATION> has also provided 
assistance to <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, he said, through a <DATE>1992</DATE> 
contribution of Can<MONEY>$800,000</MONEY> to the <ORGANIZATION>Inter-American Drug Control 
Commission</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>CICAD</ORGANIZATION>) and Can<MONEY>$2.5 million</MONEY> to the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations 
International Drug Control Programme</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>UNDCP</ORGANIZATION>). 
  <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Nadeau</PERSON>, is also discussing with <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> the setting up [of] a communications trunking system 
linking the protective services and perhaps Customs and Excise. 
  Press officer at the <ORGANIZATION>British High Commission Simon Bond</ORGANIZATION> said 
that the <ORGANIZATION>UK</ORGANIZATION> is placing emphasis on training especially in money 
laundering within the Customs and <ORGANIZATION>Excise Division</ORGANIZATION>. 
  "In the past we have given small-scale material assistance 
to 
the police and <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION>. But more significant from the <ORGANIZATION>UK</ORGANIZATION>'s 
point of view is training. We also give advice in terms of 
legislative drafting in the drug area," Bond said. 
  Besides donating vehicles and equipment to the protective 
services, the <ORGANIZATION>US Government</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>August</DATE> funded a US$18,000 drug 
prevention programme aimed at young people. 

</TEXT>

