<H3> <TI>   Government To Accelerate Debt Collection Efforts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601031294 Bridgetown CANA in English 2155 GMT 25 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601031294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<FP=106> [Report by <PERSON>Linda Hutchinson</PERSON>] </F>
  [Text] <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, 25 Jan, <LOCATION>CANA</LOCATION> -- The 
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Tobago Government</ORGANIZATION> will accelerate its efforts to 
recover money owed to it by at least six <ORGANIZATION>Caribbean Community</ORGANIZATION> 
(<ORGANIZATION>Caricom</ORGANIZATION>) countries, a government minister reported <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
  "This process was started by the <ORGANIZATION>Ministry of Finance</ORGANIZATION> in 
<DATE>1993</DATE>. In <DATE>1994</DATE>, the minister of finance will attempt to 
accelerate the process through direct contact with his 
counterparts in the defaulting countries," Junior Finance 
Minister <PERSON>Ken Valley</PERSON> said in the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. 
  "These efforts are expected to culminate in <DATE>1994</DATE> with the 
full regularisation of the arrears." He named <LOCATION>Antigua</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Barbuda</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Dominica</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>St. Vincent</PERSON> 
and the <LOCATION>Grenadines</LOCATION> as countries not currently servicing all of 
their liabilities to <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>. 
  "In some instances, no terms and conditions were determined 
for the repayment of the advances," he reported. "It is also the 
case in many instances that the countries defaulted several 
years ago. At this point, therefore, it has become necessary to 
verify the outstanding balances before the full recovery can be 
negotiated." At the end of <DATE>December last year</DATE>, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>517 <MONEY>million 
dollars</MONEY> was due to <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> by its <ORGANIZATION>Caricom</ORGANIZATION> partners. 
The money represents only the bilateral portion of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>'s debt portfolio. The multilateral arrears under the 
collapsed <ORGANIZATION>Caricom</ORGANIZATION> multilateral clearing facility amounted to 
almost <MONEY>33 million dollars</MONEY> at the end of <DATE>last year</DATE>. 
  Out of the indebted countries, only <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>St. Kitts</LOCATION> are 
fully current and to-date they have repaid principal sums of <MONEY>TT 
65,620 dollars</MONEY> and <MONEY>1,555,914 dollars</MONEY> (one TT dollar = 17.5 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 
cents) respectively on the original loan balances, the minister 
said. <LOCATION>Antigua</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Barbuda</LOCATION> owed <MONEY>U.S.2.5 million dollars</MONEY>; <MONEY>Dominica 
1.3 million dollars</MONEY>; <LOCATION>Grenada</LOCATION> over <MONEY>600,000 dollars</MONEY>; <LOCATION>Jamaica</LOCATION> 
97,000 dollars; <LOCATION>St. Lucia</LOCATION> 388,000 dollars; and <PERSON>St. Vincent</PERSON> and 
the <ORGANIZATION>Grenadines</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>100,000 dollars</MONEY>. The <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Tobago 
Government</ORGANIZATION> was expected to sign, early this year, a bilateral 
agreement with the Government of <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION>, whose bilateral 
liability to the government here and the central bank was 
<ORGANIZATION>U.S.</ORGANIZATION><MONEY>487 million dollars</MONEY> or <PERCENT>94 percent</PERCENT> of the total debt. The 
<LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> debt was restructured in <DATE>1989</DATE> but subsequently fell into 
arrears. In <DATE>August last year</DATE>, a team of government officials 
from <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> met with Guyanese counterparts to negotiate a 
memorandum of understanding for the consolidation of the debt. A 
memorandum was signed by both governments and forms the basis of 
a bilateral agreement between both countries. 
  The agreement provides for the liquidation of the arrears of 
<MONEY>34.5 million dollars</MONEY> which was due from <DATE>August 1990</DATE> to <DATE>July 
1993</DATE>. The agreement provides for a rescheduling of these arrears 
over a twelve-year period with a six-month moratorium on 
principal repayment. The <DATE>1993</DATE> agreement also provides for two 
semi-annual payments of <MONEY>10.5 million dollars</MONEY> in <DATE>1994</DATE> and similar 
amounts in <DATE>1995</DATE> and <DATE>1996</DATE>. 
  "Payments falling due under this agreement may be reduced by 
a range of debt conversion techniques including debt-equity 
swaps," said <ORGANIZATION>Valley</ORGANIZATION>. In pursuit of debt-equity swap 
opportunities, in <DATE>March this year</DATE>, the government is mounting an 
investment and trade mission to <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION>. The aim of the mission 
is to identify businesses in <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> in which the participants, 
both from the private and state enterprises sectors, will be 
prepared to make equity investments." 
  With regard to the recovery of the amounts due to the 
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Tobago Government</ORGANIZATION> and central bank by the 
government and <ORGANIZATION>Central Bank of Barbados</ORGANIZATION>, both governments last 
<DATE>December</DATE> signed a memorandum of understanding. The memorandum 
provides for the set-off of the government of <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>'s share of the liability of the cargo airline Caricargo 
to the <ORGANIZATION>Barbados National Bank</ORGANIZATION> against the debt of the Government 
of <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Central Bank of Barbados</ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>. 
  Caricargo's debt to the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Barbados</ORGANIZATION> is <MONEY>Bds59 million 
dollars</MONEY> (one <ORGANIZATION>Bds</ORGANIZATION> dollar = 50 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> cents) with <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and 
<LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>'s share being <MONEY>29.5 million dollars</MONEY>. 
  The debt set-off will result in <LOCATION>Barbados</LOCATION>' <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>25 million 
dollar liability being reduced by <ORGANIZATION>U.S.</ORGANIZATION><MONEY>15.3 million dollars</MONEY>. 

</TEXT>

