<HEAD>Gunmen Fire on President's Car, No One Injured</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ Assailants shot into President
<PERSON>Noor Hassanali</PERSON>'s limousine, but the president was not inside and his
wife narrowly escaped the attack unharmed, police said.
   Prime Minister <PERSON>A.N.R. Robinson</PERSON> refused to speculate on a motive
for the attack but told Parliament <DATE>Friday</DATE> that ``all measures to
catch the perpetrators have been put in place, and I urge the public
to remain calm.''
   The attack occurred <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> when <PERSON>Hassanali</PERSON>'s wife,
<PERSON>Zaylahar</PERSON>, 65, was returning home in the limousine. Police
Superintendent <PERSON>Sorzano Araetes</PERSON> said three men attacked 200 yards
from the couple's home on the outskirts of <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>.
   ``A white <ORGANIZATION>Mazda</ORGANIZATION> vehicle pulled up alongside and shots were fired
into the presidential car, barely missing the president's wife,''
and other bullets hit the side of the limousine, <PERSON>Araetes</PERSON> said.
   The chauffeur also escaped injury, he said.
   Araetes said police found the attack car <DATE>Friday</DATE>, with AK-47 shell
casings inside.
   Hassanali, 68, a retired <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> judge, became president in
<DATE>1987</DATE> and has avoided controversy. The post of is ceremonial.
   <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION>, a two-island state of 1.2 million people in
the southern <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> off <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>, gained independence from
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1962</DATE>.
</TEXT>
