<H3> <TI>   New Passports To Combat Fraudulent U.S. Visas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1301013094 Bridgetown CANA in English 2149 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL1301013094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FP=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Port-of-Spain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>, 12 Jan, <LOCATION>CANA</LOCATION> -- The 
<LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Tobago Government</ORGANIZATION> will issue new passports from the 
beginning of next month to combat passport fraud. 
  "In <DATE>1993</DATE> alone, over 300 cases of passport fraud came to our 
attention and for the first ten days of <DATE>1994</DATE>, 18 cases have been 
reported, " Chief Immigration Officer <PERSON>Arthur Harper</PERSON> told 
reporters on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. 
  <PERSON>Harper</PERSON> said passports were being stolen to get the <LOCATION>United 
States</LOCATION> visas which were then inserted into a fradulent passport 
and sold to members of the public for as high as 10,000 <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Tobago</LOCATION> dollars (one TT dollar - <MONEY>17.5 US cents</MONEY>). 
  The Immigration chief said the passports which were being 
printed by a firm in the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION>, had a number of 
built-in security features and were virtually tamper-proof. 
  Persons over 16 years old who have never owned a passport or 
whose passport has expired will have to pay <MONEY>150 dollars</MONEY> while 
persons under 16 years would have to pay <MONEY>75 dollars</MONEY>. 
  The holders of unexpired passports who are over 16 years 
will be required to pay <MONEY>100 dollars</MONEY> for the new passport and 
persons under 16 years will pay <MONEY>50 dollars</MONEY>. 
  <PERSON>Harper</PERSON> said all passports issued before Immigration started 
handing out the new ones will be declared null and void on <DATE>June 
30, 1995</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

