<HEAD>Moslems Hold Government Hostages in Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISTER HUGHES</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> (AP) _ Moslem extremists who stormed
into <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> firing automatic weapons held the prime minister
and other officials hostage <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>'s archbishop said
the rebels had wired the captives with explosives.
   The rebels said they had overthrown the government in the attack
<DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, but Education Minister <PERSON>Clive Pantin</PERSON> said <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
that the government had not fallen and was in control of the
situation.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> said several people were wounded, and a news
report said three people were killed.
   After bursting into the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> building <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>,
the rebels from the Black Moslem group took Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur
N. Robinson</PERSON> and members of his Cabinet hostage. Some captives were
apparently being held in the <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> building called <ORGANIZATION>Red House</ORGANIZATION>
and others in a TV station.
   Archbishop <PERSON>Anthony Pantin</PERSON> said on government radio he talked to
coup leader <PERSON>Abu Bakr</PERSON> for 25 minutes <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>. He said
<PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> told him the TV building was surrounded by men with guns and
he would detonate the captives and himself if an attack was
launched.
   ``He has informed me that the prime minister and other
parliamentarians in the <ORGANIZATION>Red House</ORGANIZATION> are wired up with explosives,''
<PERSON>Pantin</PERSON> said.
   Police superintendent <PERSON>Leonard Taylor</PERSON> imposed a curfew until <TIME>1
p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. Acting President <PERSON>Joseph Emmanuel Carter</PERSON> declared a
state of emergency <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> and put the country's
5,000-member army and 1,500-member police on alert. <PERSON>Carter</PERSON> was
serving as president while President <PERSON>Noor Hassanali</PERSON> was in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
