<HEAD>Alleged Arms Supplier For Trinidad Revolt Arrested Here</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the arsenal used in a failed coup attempt
in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> by Moslem extremists was purchased at gun shows and
shops throughout <LOCATION>South Florida</LOCATION>, says a complaint against the
alleged chief supplier.
   <PERSON>Louis Haneef</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Pompano Beach</LOCATION> was arrested early <DATE>Thursday</DATE> during
a raid on his home, said federal agents.
   The federal complaint against <PERSON>Haneef</PERSON> also includes a warrant for
the leader of the revolt, <PERSON>Yasin Abu Bakr</PERSON>, a former <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>
policeman who took the island nation's prime minister prisoner for
six days in <DATE>July</DATE> before surrendering.
   Of the 135 weapons confiscated in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> after the revolt
collapsed, 105 were traced to purchases made in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> by <PERSON>Haneef</PERSON>,
said <PERSON>Joe Vince</PERSON>, assistant special agent in charge of the <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>
office of the <ORGANIZATION>Bureau of Alcohol</ORGANIZATION>, Tobacco and Firearms.
   ``He was supplying the weapons that were used in the
insurrection - there is no question about it,'' the agent said.
   The arrest shows the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> will not tolerate gun
smuggling, said <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON>Dexter Lehtinen</PERSON>.
   ``We are no longer going to allow <LOCATION>South Florida</LOCATION> to be used as a
Mecca for people to purchase weapons to be used for narcotics
traffickers ... or people planning rebellions anywhere in the
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> or in the Americas,'' <PERSON>Lehtinen</PERSON> said.
   Haneef bought at least 200 assault rifles and other firearms and
the <ORGANIZATION>ATF</ORGANIZATION> is seeking the missing guns, said <PERSON>Vince</PERSON>. He also purchased
250,000 rounds of ammunition, along with electronic equipment that
included hand-held radios.
   One key question was where <PERSON>Haneef</PERSON> obtained the approximately
<MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> in <MONEY>$100</MONEY> bills he used to buy the weapons in <LOCATION>Dade</LOCATION> and
Broward county gun shows and weapons shops, <PERSON>Vince</PERSON> said.
   Trinidad officials said <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> and many of his men had visited
<LOCATION>Libya</LOCATION> and received training and money there, although they have
found no evidence <PERSON>Moammar Gadhafi</PERSON> was behind the coup attempt.
   Haneef's money was drawn on a bank in the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> nation of
<LOCATION>Bahrain</LOCATION>, but its original source was still part of the
investigation, he said.
   The federal complaint, along with <PERSON>Haneef</PERSON> and <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>, names <PERSON>Billaal
Abdullah</PERSON>, another leader of the revolt, and <PERSON>Riad Ali</PERSON>, both of whom
are also imprisoned in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION>.
   Haneef was originally from <LOCATION>St. Louis</LOCATION>, and changed his name from
<PERSON>Louis Cole</PERSON> when he became a Moslem, <PERSON>Vince</PERSON> said. He added that the
complaint would eventually be presented to a grand jury for
indictments.
   The men are accused of gun control and arms export violations,
said <PERSON>Vince</PERSON>.
   The investigation began in <DATE>October 1989</DATE> when a <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION> police
officer became suspicious of large gun purchases <PERSON>Haneef</PERSON> made at a
weapons show, according to an affidavit by <ORGANIZATION>ATF</ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON>Thomas Bailey</PERSON>.
   Haneef was interviewed and said the weapons were for a gun club,
but the agency began surveillance. He ultimately bought about 200
weapons, including AK-47 and Ruger Mini-14 assault rifles,
shotguns, M-1 carbines and large-caliber pistols.
   The weapons and ammunition were allegedly smuggled out of the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> in <DATE>April</DATE> aboard a freighter, hidden in hollowed-out
wall boards, <PERSON>Vince</PERSON> said. He said investigators had obtained a
warrant in hopes of placing an electronic tracer on the shipment,
but it had left port before they got there.
   The rebellion in <LOCATION>Trinidad</LOCATION> broke out in <DATE>July</DATE> when <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON>'s forces
seized the <ORGANIZATION>Parliament House</ORGANIZATION> and state television, holding hostages
including Prime Minister <PERSON>Arthur N.R. Robinson</PERSON> and other government
leaders.
   They demanded <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON>'s resignation, new elections and amnesty,
but eventually surrendered on the sixth day of the crisis. Bakr and
other revolt leaders are now in jail facing treason, murder and
other charges.
   <PERSON>Vince</PERSON> said he did not expect <PERSON>Bakr</PERSON> to be extradited to <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, but
said the warrants would remain in force in any case.
</TEXT>
